title: ApplicationServices/ForageFishSurveyPts
description: These data represent the results of spawning habitat surveys for surf smelt (Hypomesus pretiosus) and Pacific sand lance (Ammodytes hexapterus) conducted by WDFW and others along the marine shorelines of Washington State. Survey results have been summarized as presence or absence (lack of detectable) of spawn for each species and estimated length (parallel to shore) of suitable habitat (beach length). Survey effort has varied substantially since sampling began in the 1970s and site selection has been based on the presence of apparently suitable habitat, the ease of surveyor access, and site-specific construction requests. These data do not represent a uniform or representative sample of all available habitat types in the Puget Sound nearshore.Pacific sand lance and surf smelt, along with other smelts (family Osmeridae), Pacific herring (Clupea palasii), Pacific sardine (Sardinops sagax), and northern anchovy (Engraulis mordax), are collectively referred to as forage fish and are important prey for marine birds, mammals, and fish, including salmon, in Washington. Pacific sand lance and surf smelt spawn in the upper intertidal zone of beaches mostly composed of mixed sand and gravel substrates, and sometimes larger substrates. Finer-grained spawning substrates are susceptible to changes in beach sediment dynamics such as loss of source areas, interruption of along-shore transport, and increased wave energy that can reduce the suitability of available habitat. The accurate representation of forage fish spawning habitat and delivery of those data to public sources is necessary for the conservation of these species. These data represent more than 30 years of spawning habitat surveys.

title: CachedServices/PHSOnTheWebPublic
description: This data view sensitive habitats and species generalized to Public Land Survey sections, quarter townships, or townships, per WDFW Policy 5210, and non-sensitive habitats and species as they were mapped. The data displayed on PHS on the Web is for informational purposes only. While mapped data is established by field observations, the data is dynamic. Locations of species can change over time, and new observations made in the field are added to the database. Mapped points and areas are displayed at varying levels of accuracy and resolution, which is specified in the attribute table for the data. Not every parcel of land in the state has been surveyed for fish and wildlife presence. Before making final decisions about a project or plan using this mapped data, WDFW strongly recommends a field visit by a fish and wildlife biologist or habitat expert to make determinations about species presence, absence, or exact location.

title: Public_Geology/250k_Surface_Geology
description: These data contain statewide 1:250,000-scale geology data for Washington State. Features include: continental ice limits, contacts, faults, folds, and geologic units. This dataset was tailored for use at a scale of 1:250,000; use at larger scales would be inappropriate.

title: Public_Geology/500k_Surface_Geology
description: These data contain statewide 1:500,000-scale geology data for Washington State. Features include: contacts, faults, folds, and geologic units.This dataset was tailored for use at a scale of 1:500,000; use at larger scales would be inappropriate.

title: Public_Geology/Earthquake
description: This service contains six point, line, and polygon feature classes pertaining to seismogenic features in Washington State, including: 1) active faults (faults with demonstrable Quaternary-age activity), 2) active folds (folds with demonstrable Quaternary-age activity), 3) paleo-seismic trench locations (excavations made for use in studying and documenting potentially active faults), 4) PNSN earthquakes (earthquake catalog data obtained from the Pacific Northwest Seismic Network greater than 1 M and <25 km in depth), 5) relocated earthquakes (a subset of the PNSN earthquakes of accurately relocated earthquake hypocenters), and 6) relocation processing areas (areas used to group clusters of earthquakes during hypocenter relocation processes).

title: Public_Geology/Geothermal
description: This data service includes one feature class and five related tables that present information on the location, physical characteristics, temperature, and water chemistry analyses of thermal and mineral springs in Washington State. This dataset includes warm springs, hot springs, mineral springs, and fumaroles in which temperature was recorded. Data were gathered from all available published and unpublished literature, as well as recent data gathered through a U.S. Department of Energy geothermal grant in support of the National Geothermal Data System.

title: Public_Geology/Oil_and_Gas_Wells
description: These data contain point locations that represent oil and gas test well sites in Washington State from 1890 to present. Oil seeps were first reported in Washington about 1881 along the sea cliffs on the west side of the Olympic Peninsula. Natural gas seeps associated with mud cones and mounds were also reported in this same general area. Of all the exploratory wells that have been drilled in Washington to date, 249 reported shows for oil and gas. In 1965 the Jackson Prairie natural gas storage project was developed, which remains the Northwest's largest natural gas storage facility.

title: Public_Geology/Subsurface_Geology
description:
These data are intended to be used by geologists, engineers, planners, private-sector geoscientists, and the general public to identify geologic hazards, perform analyses of slope stability, downslope and downstream impacts, storm water management, and identify mitigation opportunities for construction or other land-development projects. Subsurface data is also used in mining, oil and gas exploration, carbon sequestration, and geothermal exploration.

It was compiled from a variety of sources including GeoMapNW, Washington State Department of Transportation, Washington State Department of Ecology, various counties, cities, and water resource agencies. It is not intended to be a complete inventory of borings in Washington State and, at present, includes only a small fraction of this total. The Washington Geological Survey is adding more borings to this dataset as time and resources permit.

title: Public_Geology/Volcanic_Vents
description:
This service contains point locations that represent volcanic vents and eruptive centers in Washington State. Many published sources were used to provide vent location, geologic description, geologic unit age, and material composition, among other attributes. The given sources indicate over 500 vents in Washington State. Funding for this data compilation was provided through a U.S. Department of Energy geothermal grant.

These data contain the locations of volcanic vents and eruptive centers, along with descriptive data. Each vent correlates to a unique ID, vent name, general geologic description, and specific description of material composition. Further information includes a feature type (categorical division of volcanic nature, for example stratovolcano, cinder cone, and dome), vent group (categorical division of vent or eruptive center based on geographic location), unit name (geologic material), and member (eruptive episode). Geologic age, age date, and age date method are listed where this information is available

title: Public_Forest_Practices/WADNR_PUBLIC_FP_Misc

title: Public_Aquatics/WADNR_PUBLIC_AQR_BATHYINV
description: This is a working inventory of Puget Sound and outer coast bathymetry dataset footprints for Washington State. The data come from many sources, with varying spatial accuracies. These data should be considered preliminary, and not representative of the full extent of all surveys. This inventory is in no way complete, and is intended to be expanded upon and improved. Initial focus of these polygons is within Puget Sound, the Strait of Juan de Fuca, and the Georgia Straits. NOAA has created a similar inventory for the outer coast and off-shore areas to aid in Marine Spatial Planning and data prioritization. Some overlap between this feature layer, and the NOAA inventory may occur.

WSDOT Region codes are: 1=Northwest,2=North Central,3=Olympic,4=Southwest,5=South Central,6=Eastern.

title: Topo/KingCo_Contours
description:
The elevation isolines in this map were generated from a digital ground model (DGM) that was constructed from lidar data. The full set of isoline source data contains contours at either a 5- or 10-foot interval depending on geographic location and elevation. (For a full explanation, see https://www5.kingcounty.gov/sdc/Metadata.aspx?Layer=contour005.)

This map displays various contour intervals depending on map scale, from a 5- or 10-foot interval at the largest scale, to a 100-foot interval at intermediate scales, to a 500- or 1,000-foot interval at very small scales. Negative-value contours are included.

title: ClimateChange/AveWinterTemp_CMIP3_2
description:
Historical and projected change in average winter temperature. CMIP3 projections. HUC8 geography.

Watershed averages for historical conditions (1970-1999) and the projected change for ten global models. Two time periods are considered: the 2040s (2030-2059) and the 2080s (2070-2099), based on a moderate greenhouse gas scenario (A1B). Results are only shown for watersheds for which at least 8 out of the 10 models agree on the direction of change.

title: Imagery/HXIP_2020_IR_NAD83_MOSAIC
description: Digital aerial infra-red imagery for Washington state was collected by Hexagon as part of the 2020 NAIP Imaging Program. Imagery was collected between June 30, 2020 and November 2, 2020 using Leica ADS100 digital camera systems. The project was flown at heights ranging from 16,500 ft msl to 20,500 ft msl resulting in a nominal GSD of 30cm. Four band images were collected to support both 3-band natural color (RGB) and false color infrared (FCIR) orthoimage products. Aerotriangulation and orthorectification were done with the Leica Xpro software package, version 6.4 and ortho mosaics were created with Inpho Orthovista 8.0. 4-band RGBN 8-bit Ortho images were created in a DOQQ tiling scheme.

title: app_services/oog2
tags: West Virginia,West Virginia Department of Environmental Protection,EnergyAtlas,app_services
description:
This service uses data from the RBDMS database, which was adpoted by the WVDEP department of Oil&Gas in August 2016. It is designed as a replacement for the original oog service, which used data from the superceeded ERIS database.

WVDEP will create new versions of its mapping applications to utilize this service, and the oog service will be depriciated and eventually removed.

The primary change with the new service is the data represents actual or proposed well locations, while the older service represented locations associated with permits received and issued by the Office of Oil & Gas. The practical effect is there is no longer multiple records associated with a particular permit id that plot at the same location; there is only one record and one geographical feature.

title: app_services/wetland_function_2019_wm
tags: West Virginia,West Virginia Department of Environmental Protection,EnergyAtlas,app_services
description: Wetland function was calculated in April 2019 for the statewide West Virginia Wetland Inventory using the GIS portion of WVWRAM (West Virginia Wetland Rapid Assessment Method). WVWRAM is a standardized protocol for rapidly assessing the functions, services, values, and condition of wetlands. The West Virginia Department of Environmental Protection (WVDEP) developed this method in coordination with the West Virginia Division of Natural Resources (WVDNR), with funding from the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency’s Wetland Program Development program. WVWRAM scores are designed to answer the following questions: • How effective is the wetland in improving water quality downstream, including sediment retention, nutrient processing, and pollutant removal? • How effective is the wetland in slowing and storing flood waters and providing base flow to streams? • How effective is the wetland in providing wildlife habitat and maintaining biodiversity and ecological integrity? • What is the current quality or condition of the wetland? Detailed information about WVWRAM is available in the Watershed Assessment Branch section of the WVDEP website. Fields Acres: Number of acres in the wetland, as per West Virginia Wetland Inventory Mapping. THIS IS NOT AN OFFICIAL ACREAGE AND DOES NOT REPLACE THE REQUIREMENT FOR DELINEATION OF WETLANDS THAT ENTER THE REGULATORY PROCESS. RegPrelim: The preliminary GIS regulatory score is used for planning purposes only. THIS IS NOT AN OFFICIAL REGULATORY SCORE AND IT HAS NOT YET BEEN IMPLEMENTED IN WEST VIRGINIA. This score represents a preliminary estimate of the physical, biological, and chemical functions of the wetland. The WVWRAM method requires a rapid field assessment in addition to GIS assessment in order to calculate a final functional score. Ninety-eight percent of vegetated wetlands in West Virginia score between 0.0 - 1.0. Scores above 1.0 represent wetlands of special conservation concern. DNRLandAcq: The WVDNR land acquisition score reflects the functions and services of wetlands in terms of conservation, development, protection, enjoyment and use. This score is based on the condition of the wetland (see condition score below) plus the “Value to Society” metrics for all functions. Condition: The condition score is calculated from the intrinsic potential portion of the water quality, flood attenuation, and habitat/ecological integrity metrics, plus the landscape opportunity portion of the habitat/ecological integrity metrics. The maximum score is 176. Note that >99% of scores fall in the range 0-76; scores above 76 represent wetlands of special conservation concern. BRank: Site Biodiversity Rank based on WVDNR Natural Heritage data on documented occurrences of rare wetland species and high-quality natural communities or species assemblages, including their state and global conservation status rank, occurrence quality rank, and concentrations of rare elements. Site Biodiversity Ranks (B-ranks) are designated as: B1 Outstanding Global Biodiversity Significance B2 High Global Biodiversity Significance B3 Global Biodiversity Significance B4 Outstanding State Biodiversity Significance B5 State Biodiversity Significance B6 Local Biodiversity Significance WetlCode: Unique identifier for mapped wetland complexes in the West Virginia Wetlands Inventory.”

title: aasg/WVGeologicMap
tags: West Virginia,WV Geological and Economic Survey,EnergyAtlas,aasg
description:
In 1968 the West Virginia Geological and Economic Survey (WVGES) published a State Geologic Map. The topographic base was compiled from Army Map Service 1:250,000 scale map sheets. In 1998 the WV Division of Environmental Protection (WVDEP) scanned the hardcopy geologic maps at 300 dpi, 8-bit color, and then georeferenced them. Rock unit boundaries were digitized off the images and attributed by WVDEP. The USGS-Water Resources Division later revised the attributes of large water bodies and referenced the datum to NAD83. WVGES augmented the map in 2008 to remove the water bodies and used surrounding geology. Metamorphic features were also added in 2008 along with "GeoAge" font notation to render proper geologic labelling for the map.

The attribute table contains information about the age, rock type (lithology), formal names, and coal seams of the rock units. Structure type and names for separate fold and fault coverages also exist with this service.

title: aasg/WVAqueousChemistry1_10
tags: West Virginia,WV Geological and Economic Survey,EnergyAtlas,aasg
description: Aqueous Chemistry data obtained from thermal Springs and Wells for the AASG data project. Information in the data table includes general information such as name of spring, location, analysis type, use, discharge, temperature, fluid (or free gas) chemistry (common analytes and isotopic information) and the source of measurement. The original data and metadata can be viewed or downloaded from the USGIN Repository at http://repository.stategeothermaldata.org/repository/resource/dc2950e94fd12022579c7307b626223c/. title: aasg/WVWellheaders
tags: West Virginia,WV Geological and Economic Survey,EnergyAtlas,aasg
description:
A well is a facility defined by its function to extract fluids from within the earth. A well may be a simple hole in the ground (generally not the kind of wells we're interested in here...), but in general will consist of a dug shaft or drilled borehole. Drilled wells may include one or more boreholes (well bores) that are accessed from the surface at an origin collar, which defines the origin of the well. Individual boreholes in the well my have origin points (collars) that are located within existing boreholes in the well (e.g. sidetracks). The most common situation, especially for water wells, is a well consisting of a single borehole with a collar that is coincident with the well origin.

Well header features represent individual wells, and are the anchor for a variety of observations and other features.

From: http://www.stategeothermaldata.org/data_delivery/content_models/well_header

title: DW_Map_Dynamic/EN_NAIP_2008_Imagery_WTM_Ext
description: NAIP acquires digital ortho imagery during the agricultural growing seasons in the continental U.S.. A primary goal of the NAIP program is to enable availability of of ortho imagery within one year of acquisition. NAIP provides four main products: 1 meter ground sample distance (GSD) ortho imagery rectified to a horizontal accuracy of within +/- 5 meters of reference digital ortho quarter quads (DOQQ's) from the National Digital Ortho Program (NDOP); 2 meter GSD ortho imagery rectified to within +/- 10 meters of reference DOQQs; 1 meter GSD ortho imagery rectified to within +/- 6 meters to true ground; and, 2 meter GSD ortho imagery rectified to within +/- 10 meters to true ground. The tiling format of NAIP imagery is based on a 3.75' x 3.75' quarter quadrangle with a 300 meter buffer on all four sides. NAIP quarter quads are formatted to the UTM coordinate system using NAD83, but were projected to the WTM coordinate system NAD83 (1991) by Wisconsin DNR staff. NAIP imagery may contain as much as 10% cloud cover per tile.

title: DW_Land_Cover/EN_Land_Cover2_Lev1
description:
This service displays Wiscland 2 Land Cover of Wisconsin, Level 1. Wiscland 2 is a raster representation of the land cover throughout the state of Wisconsin as of 2016. The dataset is primarily derived from remote sensing imagery acquired by the Landsat 5, 7, and 8 satellites between 2010 and 2014. Land cover was classified via supervised classification at the native 30 m resolution. The map has a two acre minimum mapping unit, meaning that the smallest feature depicted in the map is approximately nine pixels in size. The land cover data are best utilized at approximate map scales of 1:48,000 to 1:500,000, and at no less than a 2 acre minimum mapping unit (MMU).

Overall accuracy for the Level 1 classification is estimated at 93% across all classes. For estimates of class and regional accuracy, and detailed information on the map production, classification scheme, and class descriptions, see the Wiscland 2 User Guide (https://www.arcgis.com/home/item.html?id=b6cff8bd00304b73bb1d32f7678ecf34).

title: DW_Land_Cover/EN_Land_Cover2_Lev2_HS
description:

Wiscland 2 is a raster representation of the land cover throughout the state of Wisconsin as of 2016. The dataset is primarily derived from remote sensing imagery acquired by the Landsat 5, 7, and 8 satellites between 2010 and 2014. Land cover was classified via supervised classification at the native 30 m resolution. The map has a two acre minimum mapping unit, meaning that the smallest feature depicted in the map is approximately nine pixels in size. The land cover data are best utilized at approximate map scales of 1:48,000 to 1:500,000, and at no less than a 2 acre minimum mapping unit (MMU).

Overall accuracy for the Level 2 classification is estimated at 86% across all classes. For estimates of class and regional accuracy, and detailed information on the map production, classification scheme, and class descriptions, see the Wiscland 2 User Guide (https://www.arcgis.com/home/item.html?id=b6cff8bd00304b73bb1d32f7678ecf34).

description:

title: DW_Land_Cover/EN_Land_Cover1_HS
description:
This service displays Wiscland 1 Land Cover of Wisconsin, Level 2, fused with Shaded Relief (Hillshade). Wiscland 1 is a raster representation of land cover of Wisconsin derived from Landsat satellite imagery. The source data was acquired from the nationwide MRLC (Multi-Resolution Land Characteristics Consortium) acquisition of dual-date Landsat Thematic Mapper (TM) data primarily from 1992. The image processing technique followed was published in the UMGAP Image Processing Protocol (1998).

The original pixel size of the source TM data is 30 meters, however the classified WISCLAND Land Cover data (excluding URBAN) are generalized or 'smoothed' to an area no smaller than four contiguous pixels (equivalent to approximately one acre). The result of this smoothing is that any feature five acres or larger may be resolved in the data (i.e., Minimum Mapping Unit – MMU - of five acres). The Land Cover data are usable at nominal scales of 1:40,000 to 1:500,000 for a wide variety of resource management and planning applications. The classification scheme was designed to be compatible with existing classification schemes such as UNESCO's and Anderson's.

For more information, refer to the Wiscland1 User Guide, available for download together with the Wiscland1 data at this location:
https://www.arcgis.com/home/item.html?id=a74e139f8b0945eb977591a2f671aaa5.


The Hillshade used for this land cover map was derived from a 30-meter DEM.

title: DW_Land_Cover/EN_Land_Cover2_Lev2
description:
This service displays Wiscland 2 Land Cover of Wisconsin, Level 2. Wiscland 2 is a raster representation of the land cover throughout the state of Wisconsin as of 2016. The dataset is primarily derived from remote sensing imagery acquired by the Landsat 5, 7, and 8 satellites between 2010 and 2014. Land cover was classified via supervised classification at the native 30 m resolution. The map has a two acre minimum mapping unit, meaning that the smallest feature depicted in the map is approximately nine pixels in size. The land cover data are best utilized at approximate map scales of 1:48,000 to 1:500,000, and at no less than a 2 acre minimum mapping unit (MMU).

Overall accuracy for the Level 2 classification is estimated at 86% across all classes. For estimates of class and regional accuracy, and detailed information on the map production, classification scheme, and class descriptions, see the Wiscland 2 User Guide (https://www.arcgis.com/home/item.html?id=b6cff8bd00304b73bb1d32f7678ecf34).

description:
This layer displays Wiscland2 Northern Hardwoods at Level 4, fused with Shaded Relief (Hillshade). Classes are assigned colors intended to make them easily distinguishable visually. Northern Hardwoods are any combination of Sugar Maple, Beech, Basswood, White Ash, and Yellow Birch comprising more than 50% of the basal area in sawtimber and poletimber stands or more than 50% of the stems in sapling and seedling stands.

Wiscland 2 is a raster representation of the land cover throughout the state of Wisconsin as of 2016. The dataset is primarily derived from remote sensing imagery acquired by the Landsat 5, 7, and 8 satellites between 2010 and 2014. Land cover was classified via supervised classification at the native 30 m resolution. The map has a two acre minimum mapping unit, meaning that the smallest feature depicted in the map is approximately nine pixels in size. The land cover data are best utilized at approximate map scales of 1:48,000 to 1:500,000, and at no less than a 2 acre minimum mapping unit (MMU).

For estimates of class and regional accuracy, and detailed information on the map production, classification scheme, and class descriptions, see the Wiscland 2 User Guide (https://www.arcgis.com/home/item.html?id=b6cff8bd00304b73bb1d32f7678ecf34).

The Hillshade used for this land cover map was derived from a 30-meter DEM.

title: DW_Map_Dynamic/EN_Image_Basemap_Leaf_On_Index
description:
This service provides an Index to help determine the aerial photography acquisition date for 2020 USDA National Agricultural Imagery Program (NAIP) air photos of Wisconsin that display in the WI DNR Image Service “EN_Image_Basemap_Leaf_On”. The NAIP 2020 aerial photography is natural color, leaf-on, 0.6-meter resolution imagery. The image service has also been supplemented with 2021 NAIP imagery for MN and IA counties that lie along Wisconsin's western boundary.

WI DNR acknowledges the USDA Natural Resources Conservation Service for making source data available. For more information, contact the Wisconsin Department of Natural Resources, Bureau of Technology Services - GIS Section through DNR's feedback form: https://dnr.wi.gov/feedback/index.asp?MessageConcerning=GEO

title: DW_Image/EN_NAIP_2015_WTM_Ext
description:
The data source for this Image Service contains statewide, natural color, leaf-on imagery of Wisconsin with 1-meter pixel resolution, from the 2015 USDA National Agricultural Imagery Program (NAIP). Flights occurred in the Summer and Fall of 2015 for the entire State of Wisconsin. For metadata, see: http://dnr.wi.gov/maps/gis/documents/NAIP_2015_Metadata.pdf.

For more information about this service, contact the Wisconsin Department of Natural Resources, Bureau of Technology Services - GIS Section through DNR's feedback form: https://dnr.wi.gov/feedback/index.asp?MessageConcerning=GEO

title: DW_Image/EN_Image_Basemap_Leaf_On
description:
The data source for this Image Service is statewide, natural color, leaf-on imagery of Wisconsin with 0.6-meter pixel resolution, from the 2020 USDA National Agricultural Imagery Program (NAIP). Flights occurred in the Summer and Fall of 2020 for the entire State of Wisconsin. The service has also been supplemented with 2021 NAIP data for counties in Minnesota and Iowa along the western Wisconsin border. In areas where the 2020 and 2021 overlap, the 2020 Wisconsin data is on top. Use this services companion index service (https://dnrmaps.wi.gov/arcgis_image/rest/services/DW_Map_Dynamic/EN_Image_Basemap_Leaf_On_Index/MapServer to identify flight dates).

WI DNR recognizes the USDA for making source data available; for more information, see: https://www.fsa.usda.gov/programs-and-services/aerial-photography/imagery-programs/naip-imagery.

This service will be updated as newer NAIP imagery becomes available. For more information about this service, contact the Wisconsin Department of Natural Resources, Bureau of Technology Services - GIS Section through DNR's feedback form: https://dnr.wi.gov/feedback/index.asp?MessageConcerning=GEO

title: DW_Image/EN_WROC_2010_WTM_Ext
description: This data set contains natural color, leaf-off imagery with 18-inch pixel resolution, from the 2010 Wisconsin Regional Orthophoto Consortium (WROC). Flights occurred in the Spring of 2010 for the entire State of Wisconsin. Re-flights were necessary for the eastern 4 mi of Columbia Co., parts of NW Oconto Co, and the south half of Lincoln Co. during the spring of 2011. For 2010 WROC product specifications, see: http://dnr.wi.gov/maps/gis/documents/WROC_2010_Specs.pdf. For metadata, see: http://dnr.wi.gov/maps/gis/documents/WROC_2010_Metadata.htm. For more information, visit https://dnr.wi.gov/feedback/ and choose Geographic Information Systems Data as the subject.

title: DW_Land_Cover/EN_Land_Cover2_Lev1_HS
description:
This service displays Wiscland 2 Land Cover of Wisconsin, Level 1, fused with Shaded Relief (Hillshade). Wiscland 2 is a raster representation of the land cover throughout the state of Wisconsin as of 2016. The dataset is primarily derived from remote sensing imagery acquired by the Landsat 5, 7, and 8 satellites between 2010 and 2014. Land cover was classified via supervised classification at the native 30 m resolution. The map has a two acre minimum mapping unit, meaning that the smallest feature depicted in the map is approximately nine pixels in size. The land cover data are best utilized at approximate map scales of 1:48,000 to 1:500,000, and at no less than a 2 acre minimum mapping unit (MMU).

Overall accuracy for the Level 1 classification is estimated at 93% across all classes. For estimates of class and regional accuracy, and detailed information on the map production, classification scheme, and class descriptions, see the Wiscland 2 User Guide (https://www.arcgis.com/home/item.html?id=b6cff8bd00304b73bb1d32f7678ecf34).

title: DW_Land_Cover/EN_Land_Cover1
description:
Wiscland 1 is a raster representation of land cover of Wisconsin derived from Landsat satellite imagery. The source data was acquired from the nationwide MRLC (Multi-Resolution Land Characteristics Consortium) acquisition of dual-date Landsat Thematic Mapper (TM) data primarily from 1992. The image processing technique followed was published in the UMGAP Image Processing Protocol (1998).

The original pixel size of the source TM data is 30 meters, however the classified WISCLAND Land Cover data (excluding URBAN) are generalized or 'smoothed' to an area no smaller than four contiguous pixels (equivalent to approximately one acre). The result of this smoothing is that any feature five acres or larger may be resolved in the data (i.e., Minimum Mapping Unit – MMU - of five acres). The Land Cover data are usable at nominal scales of 1:40,000 to 1:500,000 for a wide variety of resource management and planning applications. The classification scheme was designed to be compatible with existing classification schemes such as UNESCO's and Anderson's.

For more information, refer to the Wiscland1 User Guide, available for download together with the Wiscland1 data at this location:
https://www.arcgis.com/home/item.html?id=a74e139f8b0945eb977591a2f671aaa5.

title: DW_Land_Cover/EN_Land_Cover2_Lev3_Broadlv_Deciduous_HS
description:
This layer displays Wiscland2 Broad-leaved Deciduous Forest classes at Level3, fused with Shaded Relief (Hillshade). Classes are assigned colors intended to make them easily distinguishable visually. Broad-leaved Deciduous Forest classes indicate areas who canopies have a distinct crown closure of which no less than two-thirds (67%) should be of the broad-leaved deciduous tree group. If the coniferous species group is present, it should not exceed one-third (33%) of the canopy.

title: DW_Land_Cover/EN_Land_Cover2_Lev4_Pine_HS
description:
This layer displays Wiscland2 Pine classes at Level4, fused with Shaded Relief (Hillshade). Classes are assigned colors intended to make them easily distinguishable visually. These are areas with Pine greater than 50%. The pine majority on a site may be a single pine species or an aggregate of all pine species.

Wiscland 2 is a raster representation of the land cover throughout the state of Wisconsin as of 2016. The dataset is primarily derived from remote sensing imagery acquired by the Landsat 5, 7, and 8 satellites between 2010 and 2014. Land cover was classified via supervised classification at the native 30 m resolution. The map has a two acre minimum mapping unit, meaning that the smallest feature depicted in the map is approximately nine pixels in size. The land cover data are best utilized at approximate map scales of 1:48,000 to 1:500,000, and at no less than a 2 acre minimum mapping unit (MMU).

For estimates of class and regional accuracy, and detailed information on the map production, classification scheme, and class descriptions, see the Wiscland 2 User Guide (https://www.arcgis.com/home/item.html?id=b6cff8bd00304b73bb1d32f7678ecf34).

The Hillshade used for this land cover map was derived from a 30-meter DEM.

title: DW_Map_Dynamic/EN_Image_Basemap_Leaf_On_Index
description:
This service provides an Index to help determine the aerial photography acquisition date for 2020 USDA National Agricultural Imagery Program (NAIP) air photos of Wisconsin that display in the WI DNR Image Service “EN_Image_Basemap_Leaf_On”. The NAIP 2020 aerial photography is natural color, leaf-on, 0.6-meter resolution imagery. The image service has also been supplemented with 2021 NAIP imagery for MN and IA counties that lie along Wisconsin's western boundary.

WI DNR acknowledges the USDA Natural Resources Conservation Service for making source data available. For more information, contact the Wisconsin Department of Natural Resources, Bureau of Technology Services - GIS Section through DNR's feedback form: https://dnr.wi.gov/feedback/index.asp?MessageConcerning=GEO
